            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "# Rebecca Kim Goldstein: A Life of Healing Through Art\n\nBorn to a Korean mother and Jewish-American father in 1975, Rebecca Kim Goldstein grew up in Oakland's diverse community. Her mother, Sun-ja Kim, immigrated to pursue nursing, while her father, David Goldstein, taught high school English. Their intercultural household celebrated both traditions, instilling in Rebecca a deep appreciation for diverse perspectives.\n\nAs a quiet, observant child, Rebecca found solace in art after her parents' divorce when she was twelve. Her middle school counselor noticed how drawing helped Rebecca process emotions, planting the seed for her future career. In high school, she volunteered at a children's hospital, witnessing firsthand how creative expression could aid healing.\n\nRebecca attended UC Berkeley, initially studying psychology before discovering art therapy. A study abroad semester in Seoul reconnected her with her Korean heritage and family roots. After earning her bachelor's degree, she completed specialized certification in art therapy while working at a community mental health center.\n\nHer career took shape at San Francisco General Hospital, where she developed art programs for pediatric patients. After seven years, Rebecca pivoted to education, joining the San Francisco Unified School District as a counselor. She found her true calling combining both worlds\u2014using art therapy techniques to help students navigate trauma, anxiety, and identity issues.\n\nIn 2008, Rebecca married environmental lawyer Michael Chen. Their relationship weathered a painful miscarriage before welcoming daughter Eliza in 2010. Though they divorced in 2016, they maintain a respectful co-parenting relationship.\n\nNow living in the Inner Sunset district, Rebecca finds community in her neighborhood's cultural diversity. She starts each day with meditation before taking MUNI to work. Weekends often include farmers' market visits, hikes in Golden Gate Park, and volunteering at the Asian Art Museum.\n\nAfter nearly two decades in the field, Rebecca recently began developing a comprehensive arts-based mental health curriculum for schools. She dreams of establishing a nonprofit institute integrating multicultural approaches to art therapy, particularly for immigrant and mixed-heritage youth.\n\nThrough her compassionate presence and innovative techniques, Rebecca has helped thousands of San Franciscans transform pain into beauty\u2014a reflection of her own life's journey across cultures, challenges, and creative resilience."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "# Rebecca Kim Goldstein's Personal Memories\n\n1. Rebecca remembers the moment her middle school art teacher, Mrs. Chen, displayed her grief-filled charcoal drawing after her parents' divorce announcement. \"This shows us how pain can become beauty,\" Mrs. Chen had said. The class's respectful silence and nods made Rebecca feel truly seen for the first time since the family fracture. This 1988 experience became the foundation for her belief in art's healing power, setting her on the path toward art therapy rather than simply pursuing fine arts.\n\n2. During her 1996 study abroad in Seoul, Rebecca sat with her grandmother, carefully folding rice into seaweed as they made kimbap together. Her grandmother, who spoke little English, demonstrated rather than explained, their fingers working in surprising synchronicity despite the language barrier. When her grandmother whispered \"just like your mother's hands\" in Korean, Rebecca felt a profound connection to her heritage. This moment inspired her later work incorporating cultural traditions into therapeutic art practices.\n\n3. In 2007, Rebecca watched as eight-year-old Darius, a burn unit patient who hadn't spoken in weeks, suddenly described his clay sculpture to the room. His small voice explaining how the misshapen figure was \"fighting the fire monster\" broke something open in her. She sobbed in her car afterward, overwhelmed by witnessing art unlock his trauma narrative. This breakthrough crystallized her commitment to pediatric art therapy and convinced her that even the most wounded children could find their voices through creation.\n\n4. Rebecca still feels the weight of her daughter Eliza's tiny hand in hers as they stood before the ocean at Baker Beach in 2013. Three-year-old Eliza had whispered, \"Mommy, the water is dancing!\" while Rebecca was silently contemplating her failing marriage. That juxtaposition\u2014her child's wonder alongside her adult sorrow\u2014taught Rebecca that joy and pain could coexist. This revelation helped her navigate her eventual divorce with grace and establish healthy co-parenting boundaries.\n\n5. In 2019, Rebecca walked into a classroom where dozens of student artwork pieces from her trauma healing program were displayed for visiting education officials. A school board member approached, revealing he'd been a refugee child like many of her students. \"I wish I'd had this,\" he said, voice breaking. That validation, from someone who understood firsthand, affirmed her decades of work and sparked her vision for expanding the program citywide\u2014a dream now becoming reality."
